The Ratio_btn_Act_and_Bud dataset (384 rows, 4 columns: assembly, revenue_item, year, Ratio_btn_Act_and_Bud) measures the ratio of actual to budgeted revenue across 6 assemblies (WA, Tamale, Bolgatanga, Yendi, East Mamprusi, West Gonja), 8 revenue items (Property Rates, Other Rates, Fees, Fines, Licences, Land (incl Miscellaneous), Rent, Investment), and years 20172024.

Assembly Distribution: Each assembly (WA, Tamale, Bolgatanga, Yendi, East Mamprusi, West Gonja) has 64 rows (16.7% proportion), ensuring equal representation.

Revenue Item Distribution: Each item (Property Rates, Other Rates, Fees, Fines, Licences, Land, Rent, Investment) has 48 rows (12.5% proportion).

Year Distribution: Each year (20172024) has 48 rows (12.5% proportion).

The Ratio_btn_Act_and_Bud is right-skewed (mean = 30.72, median = 1.0, min = 0, max = 8,617.6, 56 NAs (14.6%)).

standard deviation of 476.59 The range spans 0 to 8,617.6, with quartiles at 0.34 (Q1) and 1.6 (Q3). most ratios clustered near 02 and a long tail.

Skewness and Kurtosis: Skewness of 17.92 and kurtosis of 323.24 highlight a heavily skewed, leptokurtic distribution.

A median of 1.0 suggests actual revenue often matches budgeted revenue, but extreme ratios ( 8,617.6) inflate the mean, indicating rare cases of significant overperformance. The high skewness/kurtosis necessitates robust metrics ( median) and others methods.

Kruskal-Wallis Test (Assembly): The test yields a chi-squared statistic of 4.04 with a p-value of 0.544, indicating no significant differences in Ratio_btn_Act_and_Bud across the 6 assemblies (WA, Tamale, Bolgatanga, Yendi, East Mamprusi, West Gonja).

Despite Tamales high mean ratio (155.11, driven by values like 8,617.6) and East Mamprusis low mean (1.10), the non-significant result suggests that assembly differences are not consistent across all data points. High skewness (17.92) and outliers likely mask differences in medians (0.951.30). The tests non-parametric nature accounts for non-normality, but variability ( Tamales SD = 1,151.41) reduces statistical power.

Kruskal-Wallis Test (Revenue Item): The test yields a chi-squared statistic of 29.313 with a p-value < 0.001, indicating significant differences in Ratio_btn_Act_and_Bud across the 8 revenue items (Property Rates, Other Rates, Fees, Fines, Licences, Land, Rent, Investment).

The significant result confirms that revenue items perform differently, with Fines having the highest mean (234.59, max = 8,617.6) but a median of 0.0 (42% zeros), and Land/Fees showing reliable medians (1.13, 1.10). Licences are stable but low (median = 1.0, max = 4.5), while Investment has many zeros (48%).

Conclusion

Budgeting Performance is Generally On-Target:

The median ratio of 1.0 across assemblies, revenue items, and years indicates that actual revenue often matches budgeted revenue, suggesting effective budgeting in most cases. However, extreme outliers like ( 8,617.6 for Tamales 2021 Fines, 500 for Yendis 2019 Fines) inflate the mean (30.72) and skewness (17.92), highlighting rare but significant overperformances. Visualizations ( histogram, box plots) confirm most ratios cluster around 02, with outliers driving variability ( Tamales SD = 1,151.41).

Significant Revenue Item Disparities, with Fines Volatile and Land/Fees Reliable:

The Kruskal-Wallis test for revenue items (chi-squared = 29.313, p < 0.001) confirms significant differences, with Fines showing the highest mean (234.59) but a median of 0.0 (42% zeros). Land (mean = 5.69, median = 1.13) and Fees (6.15, 1.10) are reliable, with fewer zeros (21) and moderate outliers (max 127.5, 219). Licences are stable but low (median = 1.0, max = 4.5), while Investment has frequent zeros (48%). Visualizations ( box plots, heatmaps) highlight Fines volatility (2021 peak) and Land/Fees consistency (2024/2020 peaks).

No Significant Assembly Differences, but Tamale Leads Practically:

The Kruskal-Wallis test for assemblies (chi-squared = 4.04, p = 0.544) indicates no significant differences, despite Tamales high mean (155.11, median = 1.0) and East Mamprusis low mean (1.10, median = 1.1). Outliers ( Tamales 8,617.6) and high NAs (14.6%) reduce statistical power. Visualizations ( bar plots, heatmaps) show Tamales practical leadership (total ratio ~9,927, 2021 peak), with Yendi/WA showing sporadic peaks ( 500, 219). East Mamprusi/Bolgatanga are consistently low (means ~1.11.23).

Implication: Uniform budgeting approaches are suitable, but Tamales strategies ( Fines enforcement) can guide underperforming assemblies like East Mamprusi. This aligns with diff_btw_Act_and_Buds non-significant assembly test (p = 0.144) and contribution_to_revs (p = 0.923), where Tamale also leads practically.

Temporal Peaks in 2021 and 2019, with 2017 Data Gaps:

The 2021 peak (mean = 203.29, median = 1.1, max = 8,617.6) and 2019 secondary peak (12.46, 1.0, max = 500) are driven by Fines outliers, as seen in line plots and box plots. A structural breakpoint in 20202021 for Fines (breakdate ~0.5) indicates a significant performance shift, with potential secondary breaks in 20192020 and 20212022. The 2024 median (1.2, 60.42% over-target) suggests broad improvement, while 2017 is weakest (median = 0.6). Heatmaps show 2024/2020 as strong years (green tiles) and 2017 as data-deficient (grey tiles).

Implication: Build on 20212024 overperformance for future planning, but investigate 2019s volatility and 2017s gaps. The 20202021 breakpoint suggests policy shifts ( enforcement) that need evaluation. This aligns with diff_btw_Act_and_Buds 2021 peak (mean = 44,246) and contribution_to_revs 20202021 highs (medians 10.3512.05%).

Strategic Recommendations

Budgeting: Focus budgets on Land and Fees for reliable revenue, addressing Fines volatility and Investments non-collection.

Regional: Replicate Tamales enforcement strategies in East Mamprusi/Bolgatanga, where low ratios persist, to boost performance.

Temporal: Leverage 2024s broad overperformance (median = 1.2) and investigate 20202021 policy shifts ( Fines breakpoint) to sustain gains.
